1. First, make sure you have Android Studio installed on your computer. You can download it from the official Android Developer website.

2. Open Android Studio and create a new project. Choose the "Empty Activity" template and provide a suitable name for your app.

3. In the project structure, navigate to the manifest file (usually named AndroidManifest.xml) under the "app" directory.

4. Inside the manifest file, locate the <manifest> tag and add the permission(s) you want to auto-grant within the <manifest> tag. For example, to auto-grant the CAMERA permission, add the following line:

    `<uses-permission android:name="android.permission.CAMERA" />`

5. Save the manifest file.

6. In Android Studio, navigate to the build.gradle (Module: app) file within the "app" directory.

7. Inside the dependencies block, add the following line to include the necessary library for requesting permissions:

    `implementation 'com.karumi:dexter:6.2.2'`

8. Save the build.gradle file.

9. In your project, create a new Java/Kotlin class that will handle the permission request logic. For example, you can name it "PermissionsManager".

10. Inside this class, implement the necessary code to check and request the permissions. You can use the Dexter library to simplify the process. Here's an example of how to request the CAMERA permission:

    ```java
    import com.karumi.dexter.Dexter;
    import com.karumi.dexter.MultiplePermissionsReport;
    import com.karumi.dexter.PermissionToken;
    import com.karumi.dexter.listener.multi.MultiplePermissionsListener;

    public class PermissionsManager {
        public static void requestCameraPermission(Context context) {
            Dexter.withContext(context)
                .withPermission(Manifest.permission.CAMERA)
                .withListener(new MultiplePermissionsListener() {
                    @Override
                    public void onPermissionsChecked(MultiplePermissionsReport report) {
                        // Handle permission result here
                    }

                    @Override
                    public void onPermissionRationaleShouldBeShown(
                            List<PermissionRequest> permissions, PermissionToken token) {
                        // Handle rationale here if needed
                    }
                }).check();
        }
    }
    ```

11. Save the PermissionsManager class.

12. Now, you can use the PermissionsManager in your app's code to request the necessary permissions. For example, in your MainActivity, you can call the requestCameraPermission method like this:

    ```java
    public class MainActivity extends AppCompatActivity {
        @Override
        protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
            super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
            setContentView(R.layout.activity_main);

            PermissionsManager.requestCameraPermission(this);
        }
    }
    ```

13. Build your APK by clicking on the "Build" tab in Android Studio and selecting "Build Bundle(s) / APK(s)".

14. Follow the on-screen instructions to generate the APK file.

Please note that it is crucial to respect user privacy and follow ethical guidelines when handling permissions in your app. Always inform and request consent from the user before granting any sensitive permissions.

